<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06151236 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06151236 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Cheney  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  US; AID; ISRAEL; WEAPON  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said today that Washington will contributenearly $150 million toward development of Israel's Arrow anti-missile defensesystem, which will replace the U.S.-built Patriot here.;    Thedirector-general of Israel's Defense Ministry, David Ivri, told army radiothat the Arrow is &quot;supposed to provide four to 10 times more protection thanthe Patriot.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  U.S. WILL HELP ISRAEL WITH ANTI-MISSILE SYSTEM  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Washington already contributed 80 percent of the first phase of the Arrowproject, which cost $158 million. Cheney said today that the United Stateswill pay 72 percent of the estimated $200 million for the next stage, andIsrael will cover the balance.;    Speaking after a meeting today with IsraeliDefense Minister Moshe Arens, Cheney said Israel also will be given 10 usedF-15 fighter planes built in the 1970s.;    Cheney arrived in Israel onWednesday for talks with Israeli leaders. He said today that the U.S.commitment to Israel's security was &quot;absolutely unshakable&quot; and cited the&quot;enormous importance the United States places on the strategic relationshipwith Israel.&quot;;    The Arrow ground-to-air missile is intended to interceptincoming medium-range ballistic missiles and could become a key Israelidefense against non-conventional weapons. The missile is not expected to bedeployed until 1995.;    During the Persian Gulf War, the United States rushedPatriot anti-missile batteries to Israel to defend against Iraqi Scuds.Thirty-nine Iraqi missiles were fired at the Jewish state, all withconventional warheads despite Iraqi threats to use chemicals.;    According toa spokesman for the government-run Israel Aircraft Industries, which isbuilding the Arrow, a test flight of the missile earlier this year was onlypartially successful.;    The daily Haaretz said the second stage of the Arrowproject will focus on U.S. demands to make the rocket and the launcher smallerand more mobile so it can be transported by Hercules planes and trucks. Theaim is to create a system that can accompany some expedition forces, it said.A third stage also is projected.;    Haaretz said the U.S.-Israeli projectagreement stipulates that the United States will have full control andsupervision over Arrow technology. In addition, Israel will not be able to usethe technology in other projects or sell it to a third party.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Jerusalem  </CITY><EDITION>  Street  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910530  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  376  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday May 30, 199100151236,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>